While traditional side-channel leakage assessment relies on physical measurements from fabricated hardware, pre-silicon leakage assessment – conducted through simulation – faces the challenge of estimating real-world leakage before hardware is available. Current pre-silicon methods seek to improve simulation accuracy by increasing the design detail at a single level of abstraction. However, there is always a limit to the level of detail that can be incorporated, leaving a gap between simulation and physical measurements. We show that side-channel leakage analysis can be approached as a top-down problem, using a hierarchical assessment across multiple abstraction levels in a design, enabling to gradually uncover sources of side-channel leakage. We introduce Telescope, a top-down framework for pre-silicon side-channel leakage assessment across three abstraction levels: architecture-, micro-architecture-, and gate-level. Telescope’s primary contribution is to demonstrate the propagation of leakage from software instructions to hardware implementation, revealing that leakage does not manifest uniformly across design levels. Through this cross-level analysis, we identify the origins of leakage at each abstraction level and explore their interdependencies. This analysis uncovers three distinct leakage patterns across levels: progressive, emergent, and disappearing side-channel leakage. We demonstrate the scalability of Telescope by applying it to two RISC-V processors: the multi-cycle PicoRV32 and the pipelined IBEX. We analyze their power-based side-channel leakage patterns across several benchmarks, and illustrate practical use cases in debugging of side-channel leakage issues, and verification of micro-architecture effects in side-channel leakage.